    {
      "id": "v_t5t0UPfxnEZsi2BGgZT",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1298.546102934224,
      "y": -8505.888139170409,
      "width": 583.7037353515625,
      "height": 180,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#fff0f6",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b9c",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1303229715,
      "version": 286,
      "versionNonce": 918936573,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1768569496851,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "This will also consume from \nSubmission Queue\nand will make an entry to the DB\n",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "This will also consume from \nSubmission Queue\nand will make an entry to the DB\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "r2uRfpHrRXJvhyugqdQMR",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 583.4289154342241,
      "y": -8048.560014170409,
      "width": 2332.0078125,
      "height": 630,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#fff0f6",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b9e",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 350233171,
      "version": 1382,
      "versionNonce": 1140490145,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1768740069703,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Hence there are two consumers who will be reading from the queue. Most of the queuing server that we are going to have\nare not going to allow multiple consumers \n\n\nQ -> Why can't be multiple consumers for the same queue?\nthe problem is that most of the queueing mechanism that we see like AWS SQS(Simple Queue Service) they remove the payload\nonce it has been consumed by one, this is the property of Message Queue Brokers have\n\nWhat can be solution to this -> the solution can be hey horizontally scale our submission queue, instead of making entry in one\nqueue we will make entry in multiple, Consumer1 will consume from queue1 and Consumer2 will consume from queue2 and so on.\nThe problem is again submission service need to put an entry to multiple queue and might be 1 queue entry is success and for other\nfailure by any reason. So this solution will also not work alot.\nHence the solution is we need somehow a mechanism in which we make an entry ones but we can read it more than once, here concept\nof message streaming comes into picture.",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Hence there are two consumers who will be reading from the queue. Most of the queuing server that we are going to have\nare not going to allow multiple consumers \n\n\nQ -> Why can't be multiple consumers for the same queue?\nthe problem is that most of the queueing mechanism that we see like AWS SQS(Simple Queue Service) they remove the payload\nonce it has been consumed by one, this is the property of Message Queue Brokers have\n\nWhat can be solution to this -> the solution can be hey horizontally scale our submission queue, instead of making entry in one\nqueue we will make entry in multiple, Consumer1 will consume from queue1 and Consumer2 will consume from queue2 and so on.\nThe problem is again submission service need to put an entry to multiple queue and might be 1 queue entry is success and for other\nfailure by any reason. So this solution will also not work alot.\nHence the solution is we need somehow a mechanism in which we make an entry ones but we can read it more than once, here concept\nof message streaming comes into picture.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
