      "text": "Lets say there are 10 Million drivers. And there is a single Kafka Queue that we have, If all the 10 Million driver request will be \nbombarded to this same queue, Our server is properly scaled and from the server when we are actually adding data to the queue\nif there is a single queue, and if we will bombard all our request to the same queue, then what can be the problem -> the problem\ncan be our queue is overweighted, and its a single issue of scalability issue ,and we know how to solve scalability issue\n1 Horizontally\n2 Vertically -> but it has a limit\n\nKafka by default supports Horizontal scaling. Kafka says there is a highly likely chance that this queue might need horizontal scaling\nthat means we might need multiple queues to store our data. then all of our request will be distributed in our N queues. In this way\nwe have reduce the load on single queue. and these set of queues are eventually called as Partitions.\n\nHence Partition is Like a Out of the box solution that kafka support in order to make sure you are able to distribute your data\nin a horizontal way.\nAnd a collections of these partition can stay lets say we have created partions based on the Hash, All the riders who actully \nqualify for hash1 are going to add there payload in queue1 and likewise queue2 & ....\n\n\n",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Lets say there are 10 Million drivers. And there is a single Kafka Queue that we have, If all the 10 Million driver request will be \nbombarded to this same queue, Our server is properly scaled and from the server when we are actually adding data to the queue\nif there is a single queue, and if we will bombard all our request to the same queue, then what can be the problem -> the problem\ncan be our queue is overweighted, and its a single issue of scalability issue ,and we know how to solve scalability issue\n1 Horizontally\n2 Vertically -> but it has a limit\n\nKafka by default supports Horizontal scaling. Kafka says there is a highly likely chance that this queue might need horizontal scaling\nthat means we might need multiple queues to store our data. then all of our request will be distributed in our N queues. In this way\nwe have reduce the load on single queue. and these set of queues are eventually called as Partitions.\n\nHence Partition is Like a Out of the box solution that kafka support in order to make sure you are able to distribute your data\nin a horizontal way.\nAnd a collections of these partition can stay lets say we have created partions based on the Hash, All the riders who actully \nqualify for hash1 are going to add there payload in queue1 and likewise queue2 & ....\n\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
