      "version": 2476,
      "versionNonce": 309118377,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1769089266813,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Whenever a Produce has to  Produce some data, Producer need to tell which topic they want to add the data to. And once it\nenters into topic (Ride Request or Driver Location) then concept of Partitioning comes into the picture. According to our\npartition logic data will go into that partition inside that topic. Partioning logic same as we have read in Databases. And there \ncan be multiple consumers that can read from the topic.\n\n\nTopic -> It is a logical Group/ category which has a lot of partitions, we publish the data to a topic and subscribe the data of \na topic\n\nPartition -> It is a immutable sequence of append only events. Think about this like a file\n\n\nAgain and again we are referring this as a queue but its not exactly a queue we are just over simplifying it, Now lets try to understand\nhow exactly this partitioning works?\n    Every partition is kind of like a append only file where whatever event or message is going to come up, it appends that to a partition\nWhenever we are going to produce some message and it is sent to a kafka topic, Kafka topic will decide whihc partition we need to record\ninto and then these partition will act like a file where we append our data all together. we always add a new data all together. How message\nor Event looks inside partion, its kind of like a key and value pair along with that we have timestamp and few some extra properties that\nhave in header that actually gets appended.\n\nPartition is immutable -> it means at any point of time we have written our messages, we can't later alter due to any particuar reason it, \nthis give durability aspec to kafka.\n\nQ -> Can we delete these messages or events from Kafka? -> \n    We have to define a retention policy, because we can see it is more of like a log file system. we can define our retention policy like for\nhow much amount of time we want to keep the data inside kafka. we want to keep it for 7 day, 30 day, 90 days whatevee the time, after \nthat time our data is gone to remove. we can also define retention on basis of size.",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Whenever a Produce has to  Produce some data, Producer need to tell which topic they want to add the data to. And once it\nenters into topic (Ride Request or Driver Location) then concept of Partitioning comes into the picture. According to our\npartition logic data will go into that partition inside that topic. Partioning logic same as we have read in Databases. And there \ncan be multiple consumers that can read from the topic.\n\n\nTopic -> It is a logical Group/ category which has a lot of partitions, we publish the data to a topic and subscribe the data of \na topic\n\nPartition -> It is a immutable sequence of append only events. Think about this like a file\n\n\nAgain and again we are referring this as a queue but its not exactly a queue we are just over simplifying it, Now lets try to understand\nhow exactly this partitioning works?\n    Every partition is kind of like a append only file where whatever event or message is going to come up, it appends that to a partition\nWhenever we are going to produce some message and it is sent to a kafka topic, Kafka topic will decide whihc partition we need to record\ninto and then these partition will act like a file where we append our data all together. we always add a new data all together. How message\nor Event looks inside partion, its kind of like a key and value pair along with that we have timestamp and few some extra properties that\nhave in header that actually gets appended.\n\nPartition is immutable -> it means at any point of time we have written our messages, we can't later alter due to any particuar reason it, \nthis give durability aspec to kafka.\n\nQ -> Can we delete these messages or events from Kafka? -> \n    We have to define a retention policy, because we can see it is more of like a log file system. we can define our retention policy like for\nhow much amount of time we want to keep the data inside kafka. we want to keep it for 7 day, 30 day, 90 days whatevee the time, after \nthat time our data is gone to remove. we can also define retention on basis of size.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
