    {
      "id": "HrvIzG-h3QSCp7PlDVXla",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 955.052330432195,
      "y": 7625.704873947509,
      "width": 2585.7353515625,
      "height": 585,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#fff5f5",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bCm",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 73083401,
      "version": 1482,
      "versionNonce": 1934244809,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1769091612228,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Consumer1 & Consumer2 will read the data and but will not delete the data because its not like a queue where we can deque stuff, SO they \nmaintain something like a Offset, Offset defines that what is the last entry point we have actually read and based on that offset they move\nahead, SO lets say Consumer1 has read uptil D2 so we can define inside consumer1 that next time when you read do you want to read next\navailable data or you want to again read from begining we can definer everytime from where consumer will read. This ensures multiread capability\ninside our kafka, that one data published in the kafka topic can be read by multiple consumers because consumers do not remove it. Multipe \nconsumers can iterate this. Every partition maintain this offset.\nNow from here if we want to understand the more internal and advance concepts concepts that lets say how horizontal scaling can be done in\nkafka, brokers and all of that, before that its necessary that atlease we know that how to setup kafka, so that we can play around the concept\nthat we are going to learn\n\nHow can we setup Kafka?\n    Easiest way to setup kafka is by using Docker https://github.com/gitcoder-amit/Kafka-Docker-Setup/blob/master/README.md\n58:20",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Consumer1 & Consumer2 will read the data and but will not delete the data because its not like a queue where we can deque stuff, SO they \nmaintain something like a Offset, Offset defines that what is the last entry point we have actually read and based on that offset they move\nahead, SO lets say Consumer1 has read uptil D2 so we can define inside consumer1 that next time when you read do you want to read next\navailable data or you want to again read from begining we can definer everytime from where consumer will read. This ensures multiread capability\ninside our kafka, that one data published in the kafka topic can be read by multiple consumers because consumers do not remove it. Multipe \nconsumers can iterate this. Every partition maintain this offset.\nNow from here if we want to understand the more internal and advance concepts concepts that lets say how horizontal scaling can be done in\nkafka, brokers and all of that, before that its necessary that atlease we know that how to setup kafka, so that we can play around the concept\nthat we are going to learn\n\nHow can we setup Kafka?\n    Easiest way to setup kafka is by using Docker https://github.com/gitcoder-amit/Kafka-Docker-Setup/blob/master/README.md\n58:20",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
